[[File:Mare Favignana.JPG|thumb|left|Cala Rossa, Favignana]]

The '''Aegadian Islands ''' ({{lang-it|Isole Egadi}}; {{lang-scn|Ìsuli Ègadi}}, {{lang-la|Aegates Insulae}}; {{lang-gr|Aἰγάται Νῆσοι||the islands of goats}}) are a group of five small mountainous islands in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off the northwest coast of [[Sicily]], [[Italy]], near the cities of [[Trapani]] and [[Marsala]], with a total area of {{convert|37.45|km2|sqmi|2}}.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/place/Egadi-Islands Egadi Islands | islands, Italy | Britannica.com]</ref>

The [[Favignana#Island|Island of Favignana]] (''Aegusa''), the largest, lies {{convert|16|km|mi}} southwest of Trapani; [[Levanzo]] (''Phorbantia'') lies {{convert|13|km|mi}} west; and [[Marettimo]], the ancient ''Hiera Nesos'', {{convert|24|km|mi}} west of Trapani, is now reckoned as a part of the group. There are also two minor islands, [[aaFormica|Formica]] and [[Maraone]], lying between Levanzo and Sicily. For administrative purposes the archipelago constitutes the [[Favignana|comune of Favignana]] in the [[Province of Trapani]].

The overall population in 2017 was 4,292.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://demo.istat.it/pop2017/index.html | title = Geo Demo | publisher = Istat | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref> Winter frost is unknown and rainfall is low. The main occupation of the islanders is fishing, and the largest [[tuna]] fishery in Sicily is there.

[[File:Favignana cala azzurra.jpg|thumb|right|Cala azzurra, Favignana]]
[[File:Erice-views-bjs-2.jpg|thumb|left|A view from [[Erice]] to Favignana and Levanzo. On the horizon Marettimo is faintly visible.]]
